Time to save water! As the population increases in Australia and the rest of the world, so will the demand for water. If we do not reduce each individual's demand for water (both directly and through incorporated water), the water situation will become dire. It is obvious that we cannot increase the demand for water much more without damaging effects on the environment, society and the economy. It is very easy to blame someone else for the water situation - "if 70% of the water is used for agriculture, then that is what we should aim for" - but it is not that easy. We all depend on the food and resources that agriculture provides, and while there are definitely opportunities to increase water efficiency on the farm, the solution will require more than that. We all share the responsibility for the sustainable management of our water resources, which means using less water at home, in the workplace, at school, on vacation, on the farm, ... everyone, everywhere, at all times. Time to save water! This means re-evaluating our relationship with water and learning to use it more sparingly. Smoking bans in public places are linked to decreases in childhood asthma attacks and premature births, according to the largest analysis of the influence of public smoking bans on children's health. The finding should eliminate fears that such laws may have the opposite effect because they may lead people to smoke more at home. Several countries, such as Japan and Australia, have tightened laws on smoking in public places in recent years. Meanwhile, some countries, such as the Netherlands and Germany, still allow smoking in pubs and restaurants. Only about half of the states in the US have full bans, and there are few restrictions in the poorest nations. Opponents often claim that bans could make people smoke more at home, which would be worse for their children's health. Asthma is a major concern, as secondhand smoke damages children's airways in a number of ways. Researchers led by Jasper Been at Maastricht University Medical Center reviewed up to 11 studies that examined how hospital admissions for childhood asthma and preterm births changed after the smoking ban went into effect. Grundel forces Beetle to help him while Grundel steals his wings and will not return them until Beetle has found and captured Cornelius. Thumbelina is taken in by Miss Fieldmouse, who tells her that Cornelius is dead. The two visit Miss Fieldmouse's neighbor, Mr. Mole, who tells them about a dead bird he found in his tunnel earlier that day. It turns out to be Jacquimo, whom Thumbelina discovers is just unconscious. Mr. Mole wishes to marry Thumbelina; Heartbroken by Cornelius's death, Thumbelina agrees. Jacquimo wakes up under Thumbelina's care and goes to find Cornelius, refusing to believe that he is dead. Meanwhile, Beetle brings Cornelius's frozen body to Grundel and informs him that Thumbelina will marry Mole. After the two leave to stop the wedding, the young jitterbugs unfreeze Cornelius's body. At the wedding, Thumbelina realizes at the last moment that she cannot marry someone she does not love and refuses to take vows. Grundel and Beetle break up the wedding, but Thumbelina runs away from them and Mr. Mole.
